        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Well, from that I think I understand what's going on the technical side then. However, that means there is a problem in the [documentation](https://cython.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/userguide/special_methods.html#rich-comparisons), specifically the following line:\n\n> Use the 6 Python [special methods](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#basic-customization) \\_\\_eq\\_\\_(), \\_\\_lt\\_\\_(), etc. This is supported since Cython 0.27 and **works exactly as in plain Python classes**.\n\nSaying things are **exactly** the same does have a pretty specific meaning, and this is a case where there is a (somewhat niche) difference. So I guess the question is what exactly is the goal of supporting the 6 special methods rich comparison? If it's to match the behaviour of plain Python classes, then this is a bug. If it's to be \"close enough\", then the documentation needs updating.\n\nI don't think this would be terrible to fix though on the code side - it seems like having Cython check for `__hash__` or comparison methods on a subclass and then copy over any methods that should be inherited would suffice?",
