            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "`__richcmp__` does have a Python equivalent, but you have to go back to Python 2's `__cmp__` method, before the 6 special methods paradigm was a thing. My guess is that it just hung around in the Python C API from that time, and so Cython is forced into using it.\n\nThere's a slightly hacky solution that doesn't require visibility into parent classes. Special methods like `__eq__` can't be `cfunc`'s, so we have access to Python context things. Therefore, it would be possible to look for classes that define either `__hash__` or a rich comparison method and inherit from something without visibility, and then add in the missing methods to behave something like:\n\n```python\n@cython.cclass\nclass Bar(Foo):\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        return super().__eq__(other)\n```\n\nThen inheritance is handled at runtime, and visibility at compile time is not needed. Obviously this isn't ideal as it adds overhead, but it does circumvent the issue if you don't have compile-time visibility of the base class.",
