            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Ah, sorry, I had missed your comment where you linked to the code in CPython's `typeobject.c`. Yes, that's the code that does it. There is also a clear documentation note for both slot functions in the CPython docs.\n\nhttps://docs.python.org/3/c-api/typeobj.html#c.PyTypeObject.tp_hash\nhttps://docs.python.org/3/c-api/typeobj.html#c.PyTypeObject.tp_richcompare\n\nI think that restriction is not unreasonable – if you define one of the two, there's probably an impact on the other. So I wouldn't override the non-inheritance carelessly.\n\nWe could circumvent it in the cases when we know the base class implementation. But I worry that that condition might be even less obvious for users and lead to more bugs rather than less. Move a base class to a different module and cimport it, and it changes its behaviour? That would be very surprising.\n\nWe could also argue that Cython is more like Python than C. When deciding between the two, we usually go for Python semantics. And I don't see a truly striking reason for the different behaviour of Python classes and extension types here. If the problem applies to one, why not to the other?\n\nFor backwards compatibility, it'd be risky to change the current behaviour and changing the documentation would be easy. But looking back from the future, I doubt that we'd design the difference in if it wasn't there already. So, it seems wrong to have it in the first place and if it wasn't for backwards compatibility, we'd follow the Python behaviour.",
