        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Just advocating the other way, I think this is a problem that needs an actual fix of some sort because it breaks the main promise of \"Pure Python\" mode, i.e. being able to run the code in an interpreter as well as being able to compile it. This is an edge case where compiling the code changes its functional properties - and not even functional properties that look like they have anything to do with Cython (e.g. annotated variables) - and that seems to be a really bad thing. At least, if you present Cython as a compiler that takes Python code and generates equivalent optimsed C code.\n\nThere might be a difference for Cython's `pyx` files, of course. Here I could understand why backwards compatibility might take precedence, because Cython isn't Python, and so you can specify inheritance however you want. However, on the Pure Python mode, from an outsiders perspective, this behaviour looks like a compiler bug that needs a fix in order to maintain the general understanding of what a compiler is. Obviously that has some risk attached to it, but the alternatives (like saying \"Cython does not guarantee inheritance of special methods in Pure Python mode\") seem somewhat less palatable.",
