        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I don't think that's quite the promise of pure Python mode.\n\nIf you had a regular Python class, which you hadn't annotated with `@cython.cclass` then I'd definitely agree - those should behave as close to Python as we can properly make them.\n\nHowever for things which you have annotated with `@cython.cclass` you have to expect some differences in behaviour. For example:\n\n```\n@cython.cclass\nclass C:\n    attr: cython.int\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.some_completely_different_attr = 5  # will fail when compiled\n```\n\ni.e. it's not promising that the Cython code will behave exactly like plain unannotated Python code only faster. It's more aiming for working Cython code to remain as working Python code. Which is realistically probably true unless you were really relying on `__eq__` breaking.\n\nI'm personally fairly sympathetic to \"make it work like Python here\", just because that's mostly what we've been trying to do (e.g. with binops).  But I'm not convinced pure-Python mode is a justification either way.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-23T17:45:28Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/7627#issuecomment-4306544036",
            "id": 4306544036,
