        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Well, I did say I was advocating for the other side. That said, your example of different behaviour when compiled is a crash (OK, technically an unhandled exception...), and that feels like a different case. It's more of an unambiguous \"Cython can't do this\", and I'd say that's OK. Cython is only capable of compiling a subset of Python, after all, and that's Cython making it clear that this is outside the subset of allowable behaviour. Or in other words, because that example doesn't actually *run* under Cython compilation, it doesn't break the promise of Pure Python mode.\n\nThe problem with the `__hash__`/`__eq__` example is that Cython successfully compiles it and runs the modified behaviour *without* any warning to the user that the behaviour has been modified. That's what feels like a bad thing for a compiler to do.\n\nNow, when I say \"fix\", it might not require a change in how Cython handles this behaviour. The real problem is that if the user isn't familiar with how Cython works (i.e. compiling all comparison methods into a `richcmp` method) and how CPython handles extension types (prohibiting inheritance of `hash` or `richcmp` if the other is defined), they have no way of knowing that this is a problem. That could be addressed by emitting a warning during compile time, or perhaps even catching this as a compile time error.\n\nSo perhaps the way to \"fix\" this while keeping backwards compatibility is just to detect classes which (a) inherit and (b) override `__hash__` and do not override at least one of the comparison methods, or vice versa, and then emit a warning in the cythonize step. That could then be revisited later on when circumstances allow, for example a major Cython revision where breaking changes can be introduced or CPython changing how it loads extension types.",
