        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Looking in more detail at the non-extension-type behaviour: if you override `__eq__` then `__hash__` gets disabled. However overriding `__hash__` _doesn't_ disable `__eq__`. \n\nYou can also explicitly set `__hash__ = None` to disable it which I suspect we don't support (at very least we don't test it).  That appears to only be for `__hash__` and no other special method.\n\n----------------------------------\n\n> what is a good way to disable eq/hash support for a subclass if the base class has it?\n\nI think you'd just need to implement\n\n```\ndef __richcmp__(self, other, op):\n    return NotImplemented\n```\n\nbut it's definitely possible there's something subtle behaviour differences I'm missing here.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-30T07:11:21Z",
