        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Having had a bit of time to look at the behaviour, my guess is that Cython's current behaviour is to return `self is other` as the default `__eq__` method; I'm basing this from the observation that in my example, under Cython `bar_a == bar_a` is True, but `bar_a == bar_b` is False. As an aside, [this is different to what the documentation specifies as Python's default behaviour](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/datamodel.html#object.__eq__) for `object.__eq__`, where it's specified as `True if self is other else NotImplemented`, but seems to match the actual implemented Python behaviour (i.e. `(object() == object()) is False` under Python).\n\nSo if the behaviour changed to allow inheritance of `__eq__` in this case, then the current behaviour could be restored by implementing:\n\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    return self is other\n```\n\non affected objects.",
